        "number": 3,
        "title": "The city's commerce in the dock",
        "range": "6:9-12",
        "excerpt": "Is there yet a man in the wicked house, along with treasures of wickedness and a short measure that is cursed? Can I justify wicked scales and a bag of deceptive weights?",
        "body": "The voice of Yahweh now turns to 'the city' (likely Jerusalem, given Micah's primary audience, though Samaria stands behind the Omride reference in v. 16). The opening note — 'it is sound wisdom (*tushiyyah*) to fear Your name' — marks the secondary indictment as a wisdom appeal: the city's failure is also a failure of basic prudential reasoning. To rig the market against Yahweh's own measurement is not just wicked; it is stupid.\n\nThe specific charges are economic. **Treasures of wickedness** — wealth accumulated through fraud. **The short ephah** — the dry-measure basket deliberately made smaller than legal, so the customer paying for a full ephah receives less than that. Amos 8:5 names the same fraud: 'we will make the ephah small and the shekel great.' **Wicked scales and a bag of deceptive weights** — the merchant carried two sets of stones, a heavy set to weigh out what he sold (overstating amount, underdelivering) and a light set to weigh in what he bought (paying less than the labeled amount). Deuteronomy 25:13-16 names this and calls every practitioner 'an abomination to the LORD.' Leviticus 19:35-36 and Proverbs 11:1, 20:10, 23 repeat the prohibition.\n\nThe theological point is precise. Mishpat (v. 8) is not abstract; it is the integrity of the ephah and the honesty of the stones. The merchants who escalated their sacrificial bids in 6:6-7 were the same merchants who weighted their bags in 6:11. Cult and commerce stand exposed as two faces of one fraud — punctilious about the altar, punctilious about the cheating. The covenant lawsuit is not about insufficient religiosity; it is about the actual structure of the people's life together.\n\nVerse 12 widens the indictment: the rich are 'full of violence' (*ḥāmās* — the same word that summarized pre-flood evil in Genesis 6:11, 13); the residents 'speak lies'; their tongue is 'deceitful in their mouth.' Three of v. 8's three terms have their opposites named here. Violence is the inversion of *mishpat*. Lies are the inversion of *ḥesed* (covenant loyalty requires truth-telling). The deceitful tongue makes humble walking with God impossible — because humble walking with God begins with truthful speech.\n\nIt is worth pausing on what Yahweh names. Not idolatry per se (though that comes in v. 16); not sexual sin; not Sabbath-breaking. The named sins of Micah 6 are *economic* — the ways the powerful structure ordinary transactions to extract wealth from the less-powerful. This is the consistent burden of the eighth-century prophets (Amos 2:6-7; 5:11-12; 8:4-6; Isaiah 5:8; 10:1-2; Hosea 12:7). Micah's contribution is to tie it specifically to the cult: you cannot worship a God of mishpat and ḥesed while running a marketplace of fraud and lies.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tushiyyah* (sound wisdom, 6:9) is a wisdom-literature term (Proverbs 2:7; 3:21; 8:14; Job 12:16) — competence, effective wisdom. *ʾÊpâ rāzôn* — the 'short ephah,' literally 'ephah of leanness.' *ḥāmās* (violence, 6:12) is the violation of *mishpat* — bloodshed, oppression, structural wrong; the keyword of Genesis 6:11 announcing the flood."
